        explanation: "The capitals of Asoka's  columns, are not characteristic of Indian sculpture, though they contain\nmany native features. The famous lions of the Sarnath column and the bull of Rampurva are the\nwork of realistic sculptors, owing something to Iranian and Hellenist tradition. The abacus of the\ncapitals shows native influence more clearly than the capital and bear animals in lively postures.\n\nHence, statement  is correct.\n\nThe capital is carved out of a single block of polished sandstone, and was always a separate piece\nfrom the column itself. Hence, statement II is not correct.\nEnormous monolithic columns bear Asoka's inscriptions, all are made of sandstone, two main types\n\nof sandstone: a buff-colored, fine-grained, hard stone from Chunar, Varanasi (erstwhile Banaras)\nVand a spotted red and white sandstone from the Mathura region. Hence, statement III is correct.",
