        question: 'Consider the following statements with\nreference to the Carbon credits:\nI. Carbon credits refer to carbon emissions\nreductions or removals measured in tonnes\nof carbon dioxide equivalent.\nII. Carbon crediting mechanisms are part of\nthe Paris Agreement.\nIII. A company is allowed to sell carbon\ncredits only to another company located in\nthe same country.\nHow many of the statements given above are\ncorrect?',
        options: { a: 'Only one', b: 'Only two', c: 'All three', d: 'None' },
        correct: 'b',
        explanation: 'The United Nations announced the approval of the first carbon credits under the global market\ninvolving a project in Myanmar coordinated with the Republic of Korea.\nCarbon credits are measurable, tradable permits or certificates that represent the reduction,\navoidance, or removal of one metric tonne of carbon dioxide or an equivalent amount of other\ngreenhouse gases. Hence, statement 1 is correct.\nCarbon crediting mechanisms are a fundamental part of the Paris Agreement under Article 6.\nSpecifically, Article 6.4 establishes a new UN-centralised mechanism (often called the Paris\nAgreement Crediting Mechanism) for trading high-quality carbon credits to help countries achieve\ntheir climate targets. Hence, statement 2 is correct.\nCompanies can sell carbon credits to other companies in different countries. Carbon credits are\ntraded globally in both voluntary markets and through international compliance frameworks like\nArticle 6 of the Paris Agreement, which explicitly allows for the international transfer of mitigation\noutcomes. Hence, statement 3 is not correct.',
        subject: 'Environment & Ecology'
