        question: 'With reference to Gravity Bomb, consider the\nfollowing statements:\nI. It follows a ballistic trajectory under the\ninfluence of gravity.\nII. It is a munition that does not have an\ninternal engine.\nIII. It can carry either conventional or nuclear\npayloads.\nHow many of the statements given above are\ncorrect?',
        options: { a: 'Only one', b: 'Only two', c: 'All three', d: 'None' },
        correct: 'c',
        explanation: 'US said that it would deploy precision gravity bombs in a war against Iran.\n gravity bomb (or "free-fall" bomb) is an unguided, aircraft-dropped weapon relying on gravity\nand aircraft speed for trajectory, rather than onboard propulsion. Modern versions, like the\nupcoming U.. B61-13, are high-yield, precision-guided nuclear weapons designed to destroy\ndeeply buried targets. They remain in arsenals, including those of the U.. and Russia. Hence,\nstatement 1 is correct.\n\nBy definition, a gravity bomb is an unpowered munition. Gravity bombs do not have an internal\nengine or propulsion system. Unlike missiles or rockets, they rely entirely on the motion of the\naircraft and gravity after release. This makes them simpler in design compared to powered or\n\nguided munitions. Hence, statement 2 is correct.\nGravity bombs are versatile delivery systems. They can be equipped with conventional explosives\n(standard iron bombs) or nuclear warheads (such as the B61 nuclear gravity bomb). Hence,\n\nstatement 3 is correct.',
        subject: 'Science & Technology'
